commitResults.messageBody:
To support the addition of social media information under `Person`, we
require a new model to represent the social media associated with a
Person.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Parser and AddCommand to handle new format
commitResults.messageBody:
As discussed in the updated UserGuide, uMessage will accept new contacts
in a different format from that of AB3.

In particular, add command no longer has a need for `a/`, `p/` and `e/`
prefixes. Additionally, the add command will accept a variable number of
`d/` prefixes, which specifies a social media account/communication
channel that the person has.

This reverts the removal of `phone` and `email` as these two were deemed
essential.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Person Model, Storage to contain `SocialMedia`
commitResults.messageBody:
Person model now can contain a list of SocialMedia models. This change
necessitated changes in Person::new, and associated classes that depend
on Person's constructor.

Morever, storage classes have been updated to store SocialMedia model.

The changes are detailed as follows:

+ Update AddCommand to accept new Person constructor
+ Update SampleDataUtil to accept new Person constructor
+ Update JsonAdaptedPerson to accept new Person constructor
+ Add JsonAdaptedSocialMedia to parse and store SocialMedia models
+ Add new getters in SocialMedia, PlatformName, PlatformDescription

What's next:

- Add UI to display SocialMedia models. (see TODO comment in
PersonCard.java)

Update tests to handle changes in Person::new
Fix prefix not being delimited by space.
commitResults.messageBody:
Prefixes should be separated by spaces even if there are no arguments
provided. For example input string `p/d/` should be `p/ d/`, otherwise,
 parser has difficulty parsing input strings.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix SocialMedia models not being stored in JSON
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, test cases passed because Person did not set its socialMedia
attribute in the constructor. Upon fixing said oversight, it appears
that SocialMedia was not properly serialized into JSON format.

This commit ensures that now SocialMedia models can be serialized, and
also fixes a few test cases that will fail because of the new serialized
format.
This fixes a bug due to getplatformDescription being renamed for style.

Since we will be implementing several commands that can target the list in AddressBook based on an Index or Name of Person, we should
refactor this targetting into a separate class.

This reduces the need to make two sets of commands whenever we wish to allow for targetting by
both Index and Name.
This adds the command to delete a person's tags.

Previously, DeletePersonCommand was split under IndexedDeleteCommand and
NamedDeleteCommand respectively. This 2 classes have been phased out and
replaced by DeletePersonCommand. The changes in the test files reflect
this.

Furthurmore, one test case was modified. Under
`DeleteCommandParserTest::parse_invalid_Args_throwsParseException`, an
invalid index format will throw a MESSAGE_INVALID_INDEX to warn the user
that the index provided is invalid since this is more useful than giving a
generic DeleteCommand.MESSAGE_USAGE.

Update UG for add and delete
Add two new observable values in Model
commitResults.messageBody:
currentlySelectedPersonProperty represents the currently selected person
in the addressbook. The currently selected person is the one displayed in
the RHS panel at any given moment. The RHS panel will observe this
property for any changes, and update accordingly if the person
encapsulated by this variable changes.

selectionIndex represents the current index selected in PersonListPanel.
Typically, the ListView in PersonListPanel already exposes a
SelectionModel for us to track and modify the current selection in a
ListView. But since we want to reduce coupling and ensure that Ui only
observes and reacts to changes in the model, we should not track the
SelectionModel in ListView, but track a separate observable value.
PersonListPanel will observe this variable, and update accordingly if
the selectionIndex is changed.

PersonListPanel will now update the currentlySelectedPerson in
ModelManager after each selection change done using arrow keys or mouse.

PersonListPanel will now update the selectionIndex in ModelManager after each selection change done using arrow keys or mouse.

ContactDetailPanel will observe the Person in currentlySelectedPerson
and load in the corresponding ContactDetailCard that matches the Person.

PersonListPanel will observe the selectionIndex in ModelManager for any
outside changes that may change it, and update its own internal index to
match selectionIndex.

View command now changes the selectIndex in ModelManager.

Add methods in ModelStub to override new abstract methods declared in
Model interface.

We want to implement indexed operations with the collection of social
medias in a given person. This commit begins the process of migrating to
a collection type that supports indices.

commitResults.messageBody:
Edit replaces the old Person instance with a new Person instance, but
the currentlySelectedPerson still references the old Person instance.

This causes a visual bug where if the currentlySelectedPerson
is the one being edited, the RHS panel does not update to reflect the
new edits to the person.

Furthermore, we should show the newly edited person instance to the user
so that they can be assured of the changes. We also set the
selectionIndex to null so the LHS does not have the selection bar over
the wrong Person.

This commit also updates ViewCommand to work with previous changes to
setSelectedIndex.

Previously, emails such as peter__jack@example.com are considered
invalid emails. However, emails with consecutive special chars do exist

commitResults.messageTitle: Make email follow RFC guideline of length 254
commitResults.messageBody:
And local part of length 64 chars.

See: https://www.rfc-editor.org/errata_search.php?rfc=3696&eid=1690
